# How to Compare Round Diamonds Online: The Online Comparison Protocol

## TL;DR: Online Diamond Comparison — 5 Steps

- **Step 1:** Filter by GIA certificate only for natural diamonds — IGI inflates color and clarity by 1–2 grades for natural stones
- **Step 2:** Set proportion filters (table 54–57%, depth 59–62.3%) before comparing any prices — these filters eliminate ~70% of poorly-cut diamonds that have the right 4Cs but wrong geometry
- **Step 3:** Watch the 360° HD video for every stone under SI1 clarity — 30% of SI1 and 70% of SI2 rounds are not eye-clean, and only video confirms it
- **Step 4:** Calculate per-carat price, not total price — comparing total prices across different carat weights creates false value impressions
- **Step 5:** Verify the return policy before checkout — Blue Nile's 30-day free return is the safety net that makes online diamond buying safe
- Biggest mistake buyers make: comparing prices across different cut grades (Excellent vs Very Good). Only compare within GIA Excellent; cut grade differences swamp all other price factors

---

Online diamond buying saves $2,000–$8,000 on a 1ct–3ct stone compared to local retail. Blue Nile's overhead is a fraction of a brick-and-mortar jeweler. The savings are real and significant.

But online buying introduces risk that in-store buying eliminates: you cannot see the stone in person, cannot compare side-by-side under multiple light sources, and must trust data and imaging to make a decision. The five steps below eliminate that risk systematically. Follow them in order.

## Step 1: Set Your Certificate Filter Before Anything Else

The first filter you apply on any online diamond search determines everything downstream. For natural diamonds, set the certificate filter to **GIA only**. Do not include IGI, EGL, AGS, or any other lab for natural stones.

Why GIA only: IGI (International Gemological Institute) grades natural diamonds 1–2 color grades and 1 clarity grade more generously than GIA. A stone an IGI grades as G-VS2 is likely an H-SI1 by GIA standards. You will pay G-VS2 prices for H-SI1 quality. This is not fraud — it is a documented, consistent grading difference — but it costs buyers thousands when they compare an IGI G-VS2 to a GIA G-VS2 without understanding the gap.

EGL (European Gemological Laboratory) inflates 2–4 grades. Never buy an EGL-certified diamond. AGS (American Gem Society) closed in 2023. Any GIA, AGS-closed-era stone with a certificate you can verify directly on GIA's website is acceptable — but GIA current is the standard.

For lab-grown diamonds specifically: IGI is acceptable and is actually the industry standard for lab certification. Lab diamond grading differences between labs are smaller and better documented. But for natural diamonds, GIA only.

### Does the GIA filter significantly reduce available inventory?

Yes — by 40–60% on most platforms. This is the correct outcome. You are filtering out overgraded stones that appear cheaper but are not. After the GIA filter, the remaining inventory is comparable on honest grade-to-grade terms.

On Blue Nile, the GIA filter for natural rounds still leaves hundreds of stones across every carat weight. A [GIA 1.00 Carat G-VS2 Excellent Cut Round Diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29090690?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at $3,230 and a [GIA 1.00 Carat G-VS1 Excellent Cut Round Diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29161966?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at $3,300 are now directly comparable — same lab, same grading rigor, honest quality comparison.

## Step 2: Lock Your Proportion Filters Before Comparing Prices

Cut grade alone is not enough. A GIA Excellent cut grade covers a range of proportions that includes both ideal and acceptable stones. The upper end of GIA Excellent (table 54–57%, crown 34–35°, pavilion 40.6–41.0°) returns maximum light. The lower end of GIA Excellent (table 58%, crown 32°, depth 63%) still passes the grade but performs noticeably worse.

Set these filters before looking at prices:

- **Table:** 54–57% (never above 58% — this is The Flash Trap)
- **Depth:** 59.0–62.3%
- **Crown angle:** 34.0–35.0°
- **Pavilion angle:** 40.6–41.0°
- **Girdle:** Thin to Slightly Thick (exclude Very Thin and Very Thick)
- **Culet:** None or Pointed (exclude Medium and larger)
- **Cut grade:** Excellent only (never include Very Good for natural rounds if budget allows)
- **Polish & Symmetry:** Excellent or Very Good

These filters reduce inventory further — typically to 20–30% of all GIA Excellent stones in the weight range. Every remaining stone meets the strict performance standard that GIA's Excellent grade was designed to certify but does not guarantee by itself.

### Why do so many GIA Excellent stones fail the proportion filters?

Because GIA Excellent is a range, not a point. GIA certifies a significant width of proportions as Excellent because their research shows human perception cannot distinguish between a 54% table and a 57% table at normal viewing. They are correct at the level of basic human perception.

But for buyers who want the top tier of light return within GIA Excellent — the range where proportion optimization actually matters — the filters above select for it. A [GIA 1.00 Carat F-VS2 Excellent Cut Round Diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28215109?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at $3,490 and a [GIA 1.00 Carat E-VS2 Excellent Cut Round Diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27878143?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at $3,540 that both pass these filters are genuinely comparable, high-performing stones.

## Step 3: Watch the 360° Video — Every Time, No Exceptions

Video is not optional. It is the primary safety mechanism for online diamond buying, and skipping it is the most expensive mistake buyers make.

Here is why: GIA clarity grading maps inclusions accurately but cannot tell you whether a specific inclusion pattern creates a visible dark spot, milky appearance, or distracting feature at normal face-up viewing distance. The same VS2 clarity grade can produce a stone that looks completely clean face-up OR one with a centrally placed crystal inclusion that catches the eye under direct light.

For SI1 and SI2 grades, video is mandatory. SI1 stones are eye-clean approximately 70% of the time at 1ct. SI2 stones are eye-clean only 30–40% of the time at 1ct. Without video, you are choosing from the full pool without knowing which group your stone falls into.

Watch the video with these checks: (1) Is the table area clean and bright? (2) Are there any dark spots visible when the stone faces directly up toward the camera? (3) Does the stone show any milky, hazy, or gray appearance? (4) Do the inclusions move to the perimeter when the stone rotates, or do they stay centrally visible? Any stone that fails these checks should be eliminated regardless of the clarity grade on the certificate.

![Round diamond online comparison protocol step-by-step showing certificate filter, proportion filter and 360-degree video inspection process](/images/round-diamond-online-comparison-steps.avif "Round Diamond Online Comparison Protocol: Certificate, Proportions, and Video Inspection Steps")

### What if the listing does not have 360° video?

Do not buy it. Any major online retailer selling GIA-certified diamonds at $2,500+ should provide 360° video imaging as a standard feature. Blue Nile provides this for their inventory. A listing without video on a significant stone purchase is asking you to make a $3,000+ decision blind — which no informed buyer should accept.

If you find a stone with ideal specifications but no video, contact the retailer and request it. If they cannot provide it, move to the next stone on the list. There is always another stone.

## Step 4: Compare Per-Carat Price, Not Total Price

This is where most buyers create false value impressions. Comparing a $3,230 1ct stone to a $2,487 0.90ct stone and concluding the 0.90ct is "cheaper" ignores the fact that you are comparing different sizes. The correct comparison is per-carat price.

The calculation: divide total price by exact carat weight.
- [GIA 1.00 Carat G-VS2 Excellent Cut Round Diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29090694?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at $3,240 = **$3,240 per carat**
- [GIA 1.00 Carat G-VVS2 Excellent Cut Round Diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25530212?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at $3,650 = **$3,650 per carat**

The VVS2 stone costs $410 more per carat for one clarity grade upgrade from VS2. That is a meaningful premium for a clarity difference that is invisible to the naked eye in a round brilliant. This is the kind of comparison the per-carat calculation makes obvious.

Within the same carat weight, use per-carat price to find the best specification at the lowest honest price. Between different carat weights, use per-carat price to understand the rarity premium — 2ct diamonds cost $8,245 per carat (2ct G-VS2 $16,490) versus $3,230 per carat at 1ct. The 2.55× per-carat premium for crossing the 2ct threshold is The Size Jump Tax, and you can only see it clearly with per-carat math.

### How do I use per-carat price to spot overpriced stones?

Within any single carat weight and grade bucket (say, 1ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent), the per-carat price range on Blue Nile spans roughly $3,230–$4,230. Stones at the top of that range have premium polish/symmetry grades or superior proportions by Blue Nile's own assessment.

If a stone at the top of the per-carat range does not show meaningfully better proportions in the GIA report compared to a mid-range stone, buy the mid-range stone. The premium is not always documented or visible. A [GIA 1.00 Carat G-VS2 Excellent Cut Round Diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112616?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at $3,370 per carat that passes all proportion filters performs identically to a comparable stone at $3,650 per carat. You are paying $280 per carat for documentation and potentially branding, not visual performance.

## Step 5: Verify the Return Policy Before Checkout

Blue Nile's return policy is 30 days from delivery for a full refund, no questions asked, with free return shipping on orders over $500. This is the safety net that makes online diamond buying genuinely safe.

Verify it is still in effect before final checkout. Return policies can change, and some promotional stones or special-order items have different terms. The 30-day window gives you time to have the stone independently appraised (cost: $50–$150 at a local GIA-certified appraiser), compare it against the GIA report, and view it in multiple lighting conditions before committing.

Do not skip the independent appraisal if you are spending $5,000 or more. The appraiser will confirm the stone matches the GIA certificate, check for damage in transit, and give you a replacement value for insurance purposes. This $100 step catches problems before the return window closes.

![Blue Nile round diamond filter checklist showing GIA certificate, proportion settings, per-carat price calculation, and 30-day return policy verification](/images/blue-nile-diamond-filter-guide.avif "Blue Nile Round Diamond Filter Checklist: The Online Comparison Protocol")

### What if I receive the stone and it looks different from the video?

Return it immediately. The 30-day window starts at delivery. If the stone looks hazy, shows unexpected dark inclusions face-up, or simply does not match the color or presence shown in the video — initiate the return within days of receipt, not weeks. Do not wait until day 28 because you were hoping it would "grow on you."

A returned diamond is not a failure. It is the return policy doing exactly what it was designed to do. Blue Nile's business model depends on customer trust, which means returns are processed smoothly and without pressure.

## How to Compare Two Specific Stones Side by Side

Once you have two or three stones that pass all filters, here is the structured comparison:

**Price check:** Calculate per-carat price for each. Eliminate any stone more than 10% above the lowest per-carat option unless the specification difference justifies it.

**Proportion comparison:** Pull both GIA reports. Compare table%, depth%, crown angle, and pavilion angle. If both stones fall within the optimal ranges, they are equivalent performers regardless of other differences. If one is at the ideal center of the range (table 55%, crown 34.5°) and one is at the edge (table 57%, crown 35°), prefer the center.

**Video comparison:** Watch both videos back-to-back. Look specifically at: (1) overall brightness, (2) pattern of dark and light areas, (3) any distracting inclusions, (4) the "scintillation" (on-off sparkle) when the stone rotates. The better-performing video wins — stone quality differences that do not show in video do not matter in real-world wear.

**Final decision:** All else equal, buy the lower per-carat price. The diamonds that survive this protocol are genuinely equivalent. Do not overthink final selection between two stones that passed every filter.

### What are the most common comparison mistakes?

Comparing across cut grades is the most expensive mistake. A GIA Very Good cut at $2,800 and a GIA Excellent cut at $3,230 at the same 1ct G-VS2 specification look different in person — the Excellent returns more light and has better scintillation. The $430 difference is real performance difference, not marketing. Always compare within Excellent cut only.

Comparing without proportion filters is the second mistake. Two GIA Excellent stones at the same grade can have meaningfully different visual performance if one has a 58% table and 41.5° pavilion versus a 55% table and 40.8° pavilion. The filter eliminates this before you start comparing.

Comparing videos filmed under different lighting is the third mistake. Some vendors shoot under directional spotlights that make any stone look exceptional; Blue Nile uses consistent standardized lighting. Comparing a Blue Nile video to a competitor's spotlight video is not an apples-to-apples comparison.

## Common Comparison Mistakes That Cost Buyers Thousands

**Mistake 1: Anchoring on total price.** A buyer sees a 2ct G-VS2 at $16,490 and a "discounted" 1.8ct G-VS1 elsewhere at $14,000 and thinks they are getting a deal. Per-carat: 1.8ct at $7,778/ct vs 2ct [GIA 2.00 Carat G-VS2 Excellent Cut Round Diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29307739?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at $8,245/ct. The total price is lower but the per-carat rate is competitive. The "deal" disappears under per-carat analysis.

**Mistake 2: Buying without video on an SI1.** SI1 is the most popular clarity grade because it appears to offer significant savings over VS2 (approximately $600–$800 at 1ct). But 30% of SI1 rounds are not eye-clean. A buyer who skips video has a 30% chance of receiving a stone with visible inclusions face-up. The $700 savings evaporates when the stone needs to be returned and the process starts over.

**Mistake 3: Not checking the GIA report proportions.** A stone can earn GIA Excellent cut and have a 58% table with a 41.8° pavilion — technically within the Excellent range but at the lower performance edge. Buyers who only check the cut grade and skip the proportion numbers accept lower performance than the grade implies. Always check the proportion fields on the GIA report itself.

**Mistake 4: Comparing across retailers without certificate verification.** Any GIA certificate number can be verified directly on GIA's website (gia.edu/report-check). Always verify the certificate number from the listing matches the GIA database before purchase. This catches certificate copying and stone substitution, which are rare but documented.

> **Farzana's Verdict:** The Online Comparison Protocol is five steps that take approximately 20–30 minutes per stone. In exchange for those 30 minutes, you get: the assurance of honest GIA grading, a stone with verified optimal proportions, video confirmation of face-up cleanliness, a verified per-carat value, and a safety net of 30-day free returns.
>
> What the protocol eliminates: overgraded IGI stones, poorly-proportioned GIA Excellents, SI1 stones that are not eye-clean, and price anchoring mistakes. These four errors are responsible for the majority of online diamond purchase regrets I see.
>
> Buy with the protocol. A [GIA 1.00 Carat G-VS2 Excellent Cut Round Diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29298276?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at $3,410 that passes all five steps is a safe purchase. A stone that skips any of the five steps is a gamble — and diamonds are expensive gambles.

