## Frequently Asked Questions

### How do I compare round diamonds on Blue Nile?

Start by filtering: GIA certificate, Excellent cut, then set table 54–57%, depth 59–62.3%, crown angle 34–35°, pavilion angle 40.6–41.0°. Sort the remaining results by price per carat. Watch the 360° video for any stones near SI1 clarity. Calculate the per-carat price for your shortlist and verify Blue Nile's 30-day return before checkout.

### Is it safe to buy a diamond online?

Yes, from reputable retailers with GIA certification, clear return policies, and transparent pricing. Blue Nile has a 30-day free return policy, independently verifiable GIA certificates, and standardized video imaging. The key risks — overgrading, inclusions not visible in photographs — are mitigated by the GIA filter and the video inspection requirement.

### What is the most important thing to check when comparing diamonds?

The GIA certificate proportions — specifically table percentage, depth percentage, crown angle, and pavilion angle. These four numbers tell you more about visual performance than the cut grade alone. Two GIA Excellent stones with different proportions perform differently in real light; only the proportion numbers tell you which one is in the optimal performance zone.

### What does per-carat price tell you about a diamond?

Per-carat price normalizes for size so you can compare true value. Dividing total price by exact carat weight reveals whether a stone is priced at market rate, above market, or below. Within the same carat weight and grade (e.g., all 1ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent), per-carat price differences reflect quality within the grade — Polish, Symmetry, specific proportion optimization. Across different carat weights, per-carat price reveals the rarity premium.

### Should I always buy GIA over IGI for natural diamonds?

Yes, always, for natural diamonds. IGI certifies natural diamonds with 1–2 color grade inflation and 1 clarity grade inflation compared to GIA. A stone graded IGI G-VS2 typically grades GIA H-SI1 when re-examined. This grade inflation is well documented and consistent. For lab-grown diamonds, IGI is acceptable and is the industry standard lab for lab certification.

### How important is the 360° video when buying online?

Critically important for SI1 and SI2 clarity grades. Thirty percent of SI1 rounds and 60–70% of SI2 rounds have inclusions visible to the naked eye face-up. The GIA clarity grade tells you the size category of inclusions; only video tells you whether those specific inclusions create visual problems from the face-up view. VS2 and above can often be purchased with less video reliance, but video is always better than no video.

### What proportion filters should I set for round diamonds?

Set table 54–57%, total depth 59.0–62.3%, crown angle 34.0–35.0°, pavilion angle 40.6–41.0°, girdle Thin to Slightly Thick, culet None or Pointed. These filters select for the top performance tier within GIA Excellent. Stones outside these ranges can still earn GIA Excellent but perform below the optimal range.

### What if two stones have identical grades and similar prices?

Compare the actual proportion numbers on their GIA reports rather than just the grade fields. The stone with proportions closer to the ideal center (table 55%, crown 34.5°, pavilion 40.8°) will typically outperform the one at the edges of acceptable ranges. Then watch both videos and choose the one with better face-up brightness and more even sparkle pattern.

### How do I verify a GIA certificate is real?

Go to gia.edu, navigate to Report Check, and enter the certificate number from the listing. The GIA database returns the stone's graded specifications directly. If the specifications on the listing match the GIA database exactly, the certificate is authentic. Any mismatch is a serious red flag — contact the retailer immediately or do not purchase.

### Can I compare Blue Nile to other retailers?

Yes, but carefully. Only compare stones on the same GIA certificate. The stone ID on the GIA report is the unique identifier — different retailers may list the same stone at different prices. If you find the same GIA certificate number on two different platforms at different prices, buy the lower-priced option (confirming the return policy and overall retailer reputation are comparable).

### What is the ideal order of priority when comparing two diamonds?

Priority order: (1) GIA certificate confirmed authentic, (2) proportion filters passed, (3) video inspection passed, (4) per-carat price comparison, (5) Polish/Symmetry (EX/EX preferred), (6) fluorescence (none to faint preferred in D–F color, acceptable in G–H). A stone that scores well on 1–4 is a strong buy; 5 and 6 are refinements within an already qualified selection.

